  "prompt": "How should you treat a bump on your eyeball?",
  "response": "If you have a bump on your eyeball, here are some steps to take:\n\n1. See an eye doctor\n- A professional can properly diagnose the cause\n- Different types of bumps require different treatments\n\n2. Possible causes include:\n- Pinguecula (yellowish bump caused by sun/wind exposure)\n- Pterygium (growth that can extend onto cornea)\n- Chalazion (blocked oil gland)\n- Papilloma (benign growth)\n\n3. General recommendations:\n- Do not try to remove the bump yourself\n- Avoid rubbing your eye\n- Use artificial tears to keep eye lubricated\n- Wear sunglasses to protect from UV rays\n- Apply warm compresses if recommended by doctor\n\n4. Potential treatments:\n- Prescription eye drops\n- Steroid creams\n- Minor surgical removal\n- Lifestyle/environmental changes\n\n5. When to seek immediate medical attention:\n- Bump is growing rapidly\n- Causing vision changes\n- Causing pain\n- Bleeding or discharge\n- Affects eye movement\n\nAlways consult an eye care professional for proper diagnosis and treatment specific to your condition.",
